Over the last decades, the use of microalgae biomass has gained significant importance: they are source of a wide range of highly valuable products, including lipids, pigments, proteins, polysaccharides and phycotoxin, with potential interest for human consumption as food and as medicines. Pigments and essential fatty acids have received great attention from the researchers, especially those extracted from natural sources, as the microalgae. These compounds exhibit pharmaceutical and nutraceutical properties and are considered a safe alternative to some existing synthetic medicines, due to their effectiveness in treating different diseases. In addition, they have high commercial potential for the production of pharmaceuticals, medicinal, foods, and cosmetics (
 Talero et al., 2015; 
 Suleria et al., 2016; 
 Sathasivam et al., 2017; 
 Tzanova et al., 2017; 
 Wang et al., 2018).
